{q:'The CAM (Content Addressable Memory) is also known as:',o:['Cache memory','Associative memory','Virtual memory','Secondary memory'],c:[1],e:'CAM (Content Addressable Memory), also known as associative memory, searches its entire contents simultaneously based on data content rather than address. Used in TLBs and network routers.'},
{q:'In compiler design, the LR parsing technique is preferred because:',o:['It is simpler to implement than LL parsing','It can handle a larger class of grammars than LL parsing','It uses less memory','It is faster than all other methods'],c:[1],e:'LR parsing can handle a larger class of context-free grammars than LL parsing, including left-recursive grammars, making it more powerful for practical programming languages.'},
{q:'In power systems, the concept of \'power system stabilizer (PSS)\' is used to:',o:['Regulate voltage','Damp low-frequency oscillations','Control frequency','Manage reactive power'],c:[1],e:'A Power System Stabilizer provides supplementary control signals to the excitation system of generators to damp low-frequency electromechanical oscillations (typically 0.2-3 Hz).'},
{q:'The concept of \'amortized analysis\' in algorithm design means:',o:['Analyzing the worst case of each operation','Averaging the cost over a sequence of operations','Analyzing the best case only','Analyzing space complexity only'],c:[1],e:'Amortized analysis averages the time required to perform a sequence of operations, accounting for the fact that expensive operations may be rare (e.g., dynamic array resizing).'},
{q:'In electromagnetic wave propagation, the skin depth decreases with:',o:['Decreasing frequency','Increasing conductivity and increasing frequency','Decreasing conductivity','Increasing wavelength'],c:[1],e:'Skin depth δ = √(2/ωμσ) decreases with increasing frequency (ω) and increasing conductivity (σ). This is why high-frequency currents flow near the surface of conductors.'},
{q:'In VLSI, the concept of \'setup time\' violation means:',o:['Data arrives too early at the flip-flop','Data does not remain stable long enough before the clock edge','The clock frequency is too low','The power supply is inadequate'],c:[1],e:'Setup time violation occurs when data does not arrive and stabilize at the flip-flop input sufficiently before the active clock edge, potentially causing metastability.'},
{q:'The concept of \'Byzantine fault tolerance\' in distributed systems handles:',o:['Network partitions only','Arbitrary failures including malicious behavior','Only crash failures','Only timing failures'],c:[1],e:'Byzantine fault tolerance handles arbitrary failures, including nodes that may send contradictory or malicious information. It requires at least 3f+1 nodes to tolerate f Byzantine faults.'},
{q:'In structural engineering, the moment distribution method was developed by:',o:['Euler','Hardy Cross','Mohr','Castigliano'],c:[1],e:'The moment distribution method was developed by Hardy Cross in 1930 as an iterative method for analyzing indeterminate structures.'},
{q:'The space-time tradeoff in the Rabin-Karp string matching algorithm uses:',o:['Dynamic programming','Hashing','Divide and conquer','Greedy approach'],c:[1],e:'The Rabin-Karp algorithm uses hashing to find pattern matches efficiently. It computes hash values for the pattern and text windows, comparing actual strings only when hashes match.'},
{q:'In communication systems, the Eb/N0 parameter represents:',o:['Signal-to-noise ratio','Energy per bit to noise power spectral density ratio','Bit error rate','Channel capacity'],c:[1],e:'Eb/N0 (Energy per bit to Noise power spectral density ratio) is a normalized measure of SNR per bit, used to compare digital communication system performance independent of data rate and bandwidth.'},
{q:'In power systems, the HVDC transmission is preferred over HVAC for:',o:['Short distances only','Long-distance bulk power transmission and submarine cables','Low power applications','Distribution networks'],c:[1],e:'HVDC is preferred for long-distance bulk power transmission (break-even at ~600-800 km overhead), submarine cables, and asynchronous interconnection because it avoids reactive power losses and skin effect.'},
{q:'The Booth\'s algorithm in computer architecture is used for:',o:['Floating-point addition','Fast binary multiplication','Memory addressing','Cache replacement'],c:[1],e:'Booth\'s algorithm is an efficient method for binary multiplication that handles both positive and negative numbers in two\'s complement, reducing the number of addition operations.'},
{q:'In power systems, the concept of \'load shedding\' using Under Frequency Relays (UFR) is based on:',o:['Voltage stability criteria','Frequency-load balance relationship','Current magnitude','Power factor correction'],c:[1],e:'UFR-based load shedding disconnects loads when system frequency drops below thresholds, since frequency decline indicates generation-load imbalance.'},
{q:'The Tomasulo algorithm in computer architecture is used for:',o:['Cache coherence','Dynamic instruction scheduling and out-of-order execution','Virtual memory management','Branch prediction'],c:[1],e:'Tomasulo\'s algorithm enables dynamic scheduling and out-of-order execution of instructions using reservation stations and register renaming to eliminate WAR and WAW hazards.'},
{q:'In VLSI design, the concept of \'electromigration\' refers to:',o:['Movement of electrons in a semiconductor','Transport of metal atoms due to high current density in interconnects','Migration of dopant atoms during fabrication','Movement of charge carriers under electric field'],c:[1],e:'Electromigration is the transport of metal atoms in interconnect wires caused by momentum transfer from conducting electrons at high current densities, leading to void formation and eventual wire failure.'},
{q:'The Karnaugh map (K-map) for a 5-variable Boolean function requires:',o:['16 cells','32 cells','64 cells','128 cells'],c:[1],e:'A K-map for n variables has 2^n cells. For 5 variables, it requires 2^5 = 32 cells, typically arranged as two adjacent 4-variable maps.'},
{q:'In control theory, the concept of \'controllability\' as defined by Kalman means:',o:['The system output can be measured','Every state can be driven to any desired state in finite time using the input','The system is stable','The system has a unique equilibrium point'],c:[1],e:'A system is controllable if, for any initial state and any desired final state, there exists a control input that transfers the system from the initial to the final state in finite time. The controllability matrix [B AB A²B ... A^(n-1)B] must have full rank.'}
